Collision between particles.
	- What is a collision?
		- Direct contact
		- Interaction by forces
		- Eg.: Slingshot manouver in a planet.
	- Assume: Collision between two particles with mass m1, m2.
		- The LAB Frame of reference (R frame).
			- Initial velocity of m1 and m2 in the LAB frame (note: m2 has zero velocity).
			- Draw the collision: Before and after
			- Scattering angle of the first particle. (Usually measured in laboratory).
		- The CM Frame of reference (R' frame)
			- Initial Velocity of m1 and m2 in the CM Frame.
			- Draw the collision: Before and after
		- Calc: Apply momentum conservation in LAB Frame (vector form).
		- Calc: Apply momentum conservation in CM Frame (vector form).
	- Conservation of momentum
		- Calc: Apply momentum conservation in x-coordinate in the LAB Frame
		- Calc: Apply momentum conservation in y-coordinate in the LAB Frame
		- Calc: The ratio between the sin of the scattering angles.
		- Calc: Apply momentum conservation in x-coordinate in the CM Frame
		- Calc: Apply momentum conservation in y-coordinate in the CM Frame
		- Calc: The ratio of the masses relates to ratio of speeds before and speeds after.
		- Calc: Final speed of the first particle in function of the scattering angles (and previous speeds).
		- Calc: Final speed of the second particle in function of the scattering angles (and previous speeds).
		- Calc: Scattering angles from the initial and final speeds.
		- Calc: Relation between the frames of m1. Application of law of cossines.
	- Information provided by conservation of momentum
		- Note: Velocity can be any and alter at will and still conserve linear momentum.
		- Note: Scattering angles can turn at will and still conserve linear momentum.
		- Note: Scattering angles are provided from the nature of the force field interaction.
		- Note: Final velocity are provided from if energy was conserved before and after collision.
	- Kinetic Energy in between collisions.
		- Def: Ellastic Collision: Kinetic energy conserves.
		- Def: Inelastic Collision
			- Kinetic energy does not conserve.
			- Kinetic Energy from collision can go to another type of energy: Eg.: Internal Energy, Heat, Electric, etc.
			- Vice versa too: Energy from other sources can turn into kinetic energy
		- Def: Explosive collision (FInal kinetic energy is greater).
		- Def: Partially inelastic collision (Final kinetic energy is smaller).
		- Def: Perfectly inelastic collision (Final kinetic energy in CM Frame is zero).
		- Note: If there exists a frame in which final kinetic energy is zero, then collision is perfectly inelastic, and it's CM Frame.


