The radial equation of motion of a particle in a central force is:
$$
\ddot r - r\dot\phi^2 + \frac{1}{m}\frac{dV}{dr} = 0 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
F(r) = m\left(\ddot r - r\dot\phi^2\right)
$$

So, this is the force. But then, for a central force, we have its effective potential. And with it, we should be able to derive an effective force.
$$
V_{eff} = V(r) + \frac{h^2}{2mr^2} \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
F_{eff} = F(r) - \frac{d}{dr}\left(\frac{h^2}{2mr^2}\right)
$$

Where $h$ is the angular momentum of the system. All I did was differentiate with respect to $r$. And therefore:
$$
F(r) = m\left(\ddot r + r\dot\phi^2\right) \quad\mbox{since}\quad
h = mr^2\dot\phi
$$

Shouldn't the effective force give the force? Why isn't it?
